    # [Scene: Azure Crescent Site | Late Afternoon]

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Distant low strings, a slow, downward pull]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The metallic ping of a surveyor's rod, a diesel engine idling, gulls complaining]
    "You arrive on the headland with mud on your boots and a weight in your chest that has nothing to do with the dirt. The pilot you negotiated for—your signatures, your clauses, the legal scaffolding—unspools into"
    "real noise and moving weight. Where once you could see the slow geometry of channels and eelgrass, now there are stakes, gravel, and men in hard hats walking in careful lines."
    "Cass stands near a ribboned flag, hands tucked into her trench pockets the way she tucks away doubt. She's precisely composed, like someone who has taught storms to wait. Mayor Rosa is beside her, smile folded"
    "into the professionalism of a town that must choose between ballots and tides. A small cluster of council members talk amongst themselves, faces lit both by the sinking sun and the small screens on which they"
    "check updates."
    "Your multi-sensor band hums faintly against your wrist; you ignore it. You feel the coral pendant press cold and familiar against your sternum. It is a compass that has no answers for a compromise you both orchestrated and feared."
    show cassandra_cass_rey at left:
        zoom 0.7

    cassandra_cass_rey "This is it, Mara. Funding flows now. The living-shore elements expand under our design; shore access improves, and the boardwalk will bring tourists—jobs. We both know a purely preservationist stance would have stalled everything."
    "You hear the practiced, public cadence in her voice—the one that smooths edges but doesn't show the new cuts they might leave. You know she believes in engineered certainty, and you also know the machinery won't ask marsh grasses whether they're comfortable with being moved."
    show mara_voss at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_voss "You promised mitigations for root channels and for sediment flow. You promised adaptive monitoring—real teeth in the covenant, Cassandra."

    cassandra_cass_rey "And you'll have them. Legal covenants, audits, a trust fund for habitat offsets. We built in contingencies, Mara. This brings jobs now—practical outcomes."
    "You press the words into the air as if they're clay; you shape them and still feel the hollowness. Her answer is meant to fill the hollow. It doesn't."
    show mayor_rosa_alvarez at center:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_rosa_alvarez "We couldn't have afforded to wait longer. This gives the town breathing room—payrolls, repair contracts. We have to take that, Mara."
    "The mayor's voice is the sound of someone holding a ballot in one hand and a lunchbox in the other. She does not want to break the town or to be blamed for indecision."
    "Elias 'Eli' Calder stands close enough that you can see salt on the cuff of his flannel. He watches the machines with a tightness at his jaw you know well—his hands, the ones used to coax"
    "keel lines and tie knots, clenched into consideration. He never learned to argue from graphs; his arguments are built from experience, from what breaking planks taught him about what the sea does when you ignore it."
    hide cassandra_cass_rey
    show elias_eli_calder at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_eli_calder "They promised stabilizing work around the boatyard. They'll pay for a new slip and some of Tomas' repairs. That means my cousin Jori doesn't have to go to the city."
    "Marco, who has been hired as site foreman, laughs a little too loudly. His face is bright with the simple arithmetic of money coming in."

    "Marco" "I'm telling you—this is a lifeline. People are hungry. You can be right about the marsh in a decade, Mara, but right now the kids need mouths fed."
    "The conversation spirals—practicalities clashing with principles. You answer, but you watch as the grading lines creep closer to channels you once mapped with tape and patience."

    mara_voss "This isn't a clean trade, Marco. Once drainlines are altered, currents change. Oysters don't understand covenant language. They understand salinity and current and substrate."

    "Marco" "People don't understand sitting and holding candles. They want work. They want roofs."
    "The exchange lasts longer than it should; it ricochets from topic to topic like stones skimming a restless tide. Every voice in the cluster carries a ledger of losses and hopes. The air tastes of salt, diesel, and the particular tang of negotiations: metal and fear."

    menu:
        "Stand at the headland’s edge and watch the marsh work":
            "You walk to the edge where the grasses begin. Wind pulls your jacket tight. Watching is a kind of accountability—eyes that keep the records the contracts promise."
        "Join Eli at the dock and talk through what the work means for the boatyard":
            "You head toward the dock where Eli waits. Being close to him centers you; practical plans and coaxed optimism feel like medicine in the open air."

    # --- merge ---
    "Both outcomes return to the same narrative flow that follows."
    hide mara_voss
    hide mayor_rosa_alvarez
    hide elias_eli_calder

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A chorus of planting trowels, an undercurrent of machine rumble; birds calling nervously]
    "You choose—because it's the only choice that matters in this weather—and find yourself among the pilot strips. Here the living-shore crews are earnest and small, hands working to mattress sedge and weave coir logs. There is"
    "a tender choreography to their work: seedbeds set in a careful geometry, a hope that roots will remember how to hold soil."
    "Children from town—some hired for light work—learn how to press the bundle of spartina into mud. They are taught the same language you taught them: touch firm, don't smother, watch the ebb."
    "It is good work, real and immediate, and you feel that truth like a flaring warmth. New incomes unfurl. Nia's voice would be proud."
    "But in the same breath, heavy graders cut a new access track. The hard sea wall's base is poured farther down the headland; it sits like a jaw waiting to clamp. You notice water flowing differently"
    "where a channel runs against a concrete face. Where the current was once lazy and meandering, there is now a speed, a new aggression that lifts and carries sediment away from established oyster beds."
    show mara_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_voss "They're scouring the flats. See that turbidity? That'll bury the oysters. The substrate will harden. They won't survive this knock."

    "Site engineer" "The sediment will settle. The models predict recovery. And the wall reduces overtopping during storms."
    "You want to show the models too—the ones in your notebook, the ones with caveats and error bars and a thousand unknowns. You know models talk in probabilities, but the oysters don't live in probabilities."
    "A dockhand lifts an empty oyster crate, glances at you with a look that asks whether you will give him his paycheck or his bay back."

    "Marco" "You told us a compromise, Mara. This is giving people a future. Half of us can't look at the marsh in the abstract."
    "Your voice cracks a little when you answer. You didn't imagine that the sun would feel so much like witness."

    mara_voss "I know. I never wanted this to feel like a choice between bread and the water. But I thought—maybe—we could protect both."

    "Marco" "And maybe you did. But maybe it still cost too much."
    "The town starts to split along the lines of who gains and who loses. There are dinners where relatives do not speak; barbershop conversations sharpen into arguments. A group forms to monitor the covenants; another group signs up for extra shifts on the pilings."
    # [Scene: Dock / Aster Skiff | Twilight]
    hide mara_voss

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single cello, low and warm, then frays into minor intervals]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The slap of a rope, distant voices, a gull’s plaint]
    "Later, you and Eli move away from the active site. The salt wind is colder now; it carries the scent of disturbed mud and hot tar. You both sit on the skiff's raised edge, boots dangling"
    "near the water but not touching it. Your hands are still; the quiet between you is not emptiness but a full thing, heavy with all the small compromises."
    show elias_eli_calder at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_eli_calder "You did what you thought would save the most. You kept the pilot from being swallowed whole by the wall. We have some living-shore strips—people will plant and learn. The argument isn't all lost."
    "You feel a needle-prick of gratitude at his words, something soft uncoiling inside your chest. He is always the one who translates the world into doable things: a list of repairs, a schedule, a plan. When he says 'we,' it stitches you both to perseverance."
    show mara_voss at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_voss "But the currents changed, Eli. We lost beds—some of them old as Tomas' stories. And there are families who feel betrayed. I see Marco's face when he counts crates versus when he watches the flats. I see farmers who used to trade oyster for bread now staring at cracked shells."

    elias_eli_calder "I see it too. I hate that it hurts people. I hate that our town is riven. But leaving everything in law and hope... would that have saved anyone next winter?"
    "You are quiet because there is no clean answer. You both arrived at this shoreline with different maps in your pockets and the same desire not to lose those you love. That you did not align the maps exactly does not make either map wrong; it simply makes them incomplete."
    "Elias 'Eli' Calder reaches for your hand. The calluses on his palm match the grooves of your fingers as if they'd always fit."

    elias_eli_calder "We stay. We work. We watch. We keep our eyes open on every tide. I don't have the words to fix the losses, but I have hands and I have this town on my back."
    "You allow yourself to lean into him. In the glasshouse, your laugh would have echoed differently; on the skiff it is a small thing, private and close. There is relief in his nearness, and there is grief in what the town will remember about this season."

    mara_voss "We keep going. We keep trying. We write reports that don't hide things. We build what we can and fight the rest. And when the oysters die, we plant anew where they might take."

    elias_eli_calder "And when the town fractures, we stitch it back together, as best we can."
    "You both know how to stitch. You also know that there are places a stitch cannot reach. That ache—like the nameless bruise after a hard tide—settles into your ribs where it will be a continual reminder."
    "It will not be fixed tonight. It will be present when you wake, when you map, when you stand at hearings and read sediment reports into microphones."
    hide elias_eli_calder
    hide mara_voss

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The wind picks up, carrying with it indistinct voices from the headland—laughter and anger braided together]
    "You think of the oyster beds that once lined the flats in neat, crusted rows. You think of Tomas' stories about how the flats used to be thick with bivalves, a living kitchen that fed a"
    "town through lean years. You think of the kids planting spartina and how their hands will learn the language of mud. You think of Marco's paychecks spaced like improvised bridges across a widening gap."
    "There is tenderness in the town's new seams, and there is loss in the places that will not come back."
    # [Scene: The Glasshouse | The Next Morning]

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse piano—melancholic but steady]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The soft drip of condensation, a far-off hammering]
    "You return to the glasshouse alone before the morning meeting. The structure smells of wet glass and old soil. Inside, a single vine creeps along a broken pane, stubborn as memory. You run a thumb over"
    "the coral pendant at your collar, feeling its grooves, and for a moment you are a child again, standing at the edge of these same flats, counting shells, inventing futures."
    "You do not regret the signatures you placed—regret would require certainty that another path would have saved everything. Instead, you carry a catalog of consequences and promises. The living-shore expansions work in places—the sedge takes, fish"
    "nurseries bloom near sheltered inlets, people gain work repairing docks and walking boardwalks. In other places, the hard engineering shifted currents and killed oyster beds you cannot coax back. The town keeps talking in two languages"
    "now: job schedules and tidal maps."
    "Mayor Rosa sends a letter of thanks and a request for ongoing oversight. Cass posts a press release about 'innovative compromise.' The site boasts new hires and a ribbon-cutting. Marco buys a new set of tools"
    "and shows you his receipt with pride and shame braided through the flourish of numbers."
    "You and Eli walk together past the pilot strips. You touch a young spartina shoot and feel its damp resilience."
    show elias_eli_calder at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_eli_calder "We did what we could with the tools we had."
    show mara_voss at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_voss "We did things, Eli. Some of them good, some of them necessary, some of them cruel in ways we didn't mean."
    "He squeezes your hand. The grip is a promise and an apology."

    elias_eli_calder "If there's work to undo, we'll find it. If there's work to cushion what was lost, we'll take shifts. We'll keep the monitoring, the transplants, everything."
    "You nod. It is not a triumphal vow; it is a practical list of things that will take time and cold mornings and small, repetitive labor. It will require asking for help, admitting mistakes, and persuading people who see their losses as betrayal."
    "You memorize the sound of the town's fractured hum because memory is a ledger as well. Later, at a town meeting, voices will be raised—some in gratitude, many in anger. Some friendships will need time to"
    "be repaired. Some beds will never return. You can put your name on a covenant and on a repair log. You cannot put your name on what the sea decides."
    hide elias_eli_calder
    hide mara_voss

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Minor chords, resolving into a quiet, steady hum]
    "You close the book and stand. The glasshouse feels like a bruise healed enough to forget the scar until you touch it. You and Eli walk back toward the town center, toward the dock where people"
    "will clock in and where some will stare at the flats with a helplessness that is not shame but reality."
    "You will keep showing up. You will write audits, hold workshops, stand on podiums, and sometimes watch as decisions you helped shape rest heavy where they land. Love keeps you tethered—both to a person and to"
    "a place—and it gives you a reason to continue the slow, persistent labor of repair."
    "The town moves forward with new jobs and new scars. The pilot projects breathe and seed life in places. The wall stands, a promise of protection that also rearranged the life beneath the water. Your heart"
    "is both fuller and smaller at once—full of people you will not abandon, smaller for losses you could not avert."
    "You fold your hands around your pendant, feeling its worn ridges. It is a compass without a simple true north, but it offers orientation: not a map that removes all harm, but a way to walk in spite of it."

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: The cello returns, low and compassionate, letting the melody close with a single sustained minor note]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The tide breathing, slow and inevitable]
    "You and Eli walk back into town. You stay together. The ache stays too. It will be the shape of what you live with—and the reason you keep on mapping, planting, testifying, and loving."

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_8 at full_bg
    "THE END"
